e you've uploaded the paper <strong data-start="32" data-end="139">"AutoLabs: cognitive multi-agent systems with self-correction for autonomous chemical experimentation."</strong> <span class="relative inline-flex items-center select-none" type="button" aria-haspopup="dialog" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="radix-_r_g5_" data-state="closed"><button type="button" class="ms-1 relative flex h-[25px] select-none items-center justify-center gap-1 rounded-xl px-2 text-[10px] leading-[13px] corner-superellipse/1.1 text-token-text-secondary! hover:text-token-text-primary! hover:bg-token-bg-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary dark:hover:bg-token-bg-secondary bg-[#f4f4f4] "><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="h-[16px] w-[16px] object-contain text-token-text-primary! flex-none icon-sm"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-c74d0474.svg#554074" fill="currentColor"></use></svg><p class="not-prose mt-0! mb-0! flex-auto truncate">s41598-026-45593-z</p></button></span></p>
<p data-start="179" data-end="631">This paper is interesting because it is more careful than many recent "agentic AI" papers. Rather than simply claiming that multi-agent systems work, the authors perform an ablation study across <strong data-start="374" data-end="404">20 different architectures</strong>, varying reasoning models, single- versus multi-agent organization, tool use, and self-correction, then measuring how each affects performance on five increasingly complex chemistry tasks. <span class="relative inline-flex items-center select-none" type="button" aria-haspopup="dialog" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="radix-_r_g6_" data-state="closed"><button type="button" class="ms-1 relative flex h-[25px] select-none items-center justify-center gap-1 rounded-xl px-2 text-[10px] leading-[13px] corner-superellipse/1.1 text-token-text-secondary! hover:text-token-text-primary! hover:bg-token-bg-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary dark:hover:bg-token-bg-secondary bg-[#f4f4f4] "><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="h-[16px] w-[16px] object-contain text-token-text-primary! flex-none icon-sm"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-c74d0474.svg#554074" fill="currentColor"></use></svg><p class="not-prose mt-0! mb-0! flex-auto truncate">s41598-026-45593-z</p></button></span></p>
<p data-start="633" data-end="686">From the sections provided, the main conclusions are:</p>
<ul data-start="688" data-end="1591">
<li data-start="688" data-end="925">
<p data-start="690" data-end="925">The <strong data-start="694" data-end="718">reasoning capability</strong> of the underlying model is by far the largest contributor to success. Enabling reasoning reduced quantitative chemistry errors by roughly <strong data-start="857" data-end="867">75–85%</strong> on difficult tasks. <span class="relative inline-flex items-center select-none" type="button" aria-haspopup="dialog" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="radix-_r_g7_" data-state="closed"><button type="button" class="ms-1 relative flex h-[25px] select-none items-center justify-center gap-1 rounded-xl px-2 text-[10px] leading-[13px] corner-superellipse/1.1 text-token-text-secondary! hover:text-token-text-primary! hover:bg-token-bg-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary dark:hover:bg-token-bg-secondary bg-[#f4f4f4] "><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="h-[16px] w-[16px] object-contain text-token-text-primary! flex-none icon-sm"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-c74d0474.svg#554074" fill="currentColor"></use></svg><p class="not-prose mt-0! mb-0! flex-auto truncate">s41598-026-45593-z</p></button></span></p>
</li>
<li data-start="926" data-end="1125">
<p data-start="928" data-end="1125"><strong data-start="928" data-end="957">Multi-agent decomposition</strong> provides additional gains, particularly as experiments become more complex, although its effect is smaller than reasoning itself. <span class="relative inline-flex items-center select-none" type="button" aria-haspopup="dialog" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="radix-_r_g8_" data-state="closed"><button type="button" class="ms-1 relative flex h-[25px] select-none items-center justify-center gap-1 rounded-xl px-2 text-[10px] leading-[13px] corner-superellipse/1.1 text-token-text-secondary! hover:text-token-text-primary! hover:bg-token-bg-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary dark:hover:bg-token-bg-secondary bg-[#f4f4f4] "><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="h-[16px] w-[16px] object-contain text-token-text-primary! flex-none icon-sm"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-c74d0474.svg#554074" fill="currentColor"></use></svg><p class="not-prose mt-0! mb-0! flex-auto truncate">s41598-026-45593-z</p></button></span></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1126" data-end="1322">
<p data-start="1128" data-end="1322"><strong data-start="1128" data-end="1150">Guided self-checks</strong> improve procedural correctness (higher F1 scores), whereas <strong data-start="1210" data-end="1234">unguided self-checks</strong> are better at reducing numerical chemical errors. <span class="relative inline-flex items-center select-none" type="button" aria-haspopup="dialog" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="radix-_r_g9_" data-state="closed"><button type="button" class="ms-1 relative flex h-[25px] select-none items-center justify-center gap-1 rounded-xl px-2 text-[10px] leading-[13px] corner-superellipse/1.1 text-token-text-secondary! hover:text-token-text-primary! hover:bg-token-bg-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary dark:hover:bg-token-bg-secondary bg-[#f4f4f4] "><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="h-[16px] w-[16px] object-contain text-token-text-primary! flex-none icon-sm"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-c74d0474.svg#554074" fill="currentColor"></use></svg><p class="not-prose mt-0! mb-0! flex-auto truncate">s41598-026-45593-z</p></button></span></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1323" data-end="1591">
<p data-start="1325" data-end="1591">The system deliberately combines LLMs with <strong data-start="1368" data-end="1403">ordinary deterministic software</strong> for critical operations such as hardware file generation and stoichiometric calculations, rather than asking the LLM to generate everything directly. <span class="relative inline-flex items-center select-none" type="button" aria-haspopup="dialog" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="radix-_r_ga_" data-state="closed"><button type="button" class="ms-1 relative flex h-[25px] select-none items-center justify-center gap-1 rounded-xl px-2 text-[10px] leading-[13px] corner-superellipse/1.1 text-token-text-secondary! hover:text-token-text-primary! hover:bg-token-bg-secondary dark:bg-token-main-surface-secondary dark:hover:bg-token-bg-secondary bg-[#f4f4f4] "><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="h-[16px] w-[16px] object-contain text-token-text-primary! flex-none icon-sm"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-c74d0474.svg#554074" fill="currentColor"></use></svg><p class="not-prose mt-0! mb-0! flex-auto truncate">s41598-026-45593-z</p></button></span></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1593" data-end="2061">From the perspective of your repair-theoretic and admissibility frameworks, what stands out is that the paper is really about <strong data-start="1719" data-end="1764">iterative repair rather than intelligence</strong>. The architecture repeatedly generates candidate procedures, checks them against admissibility constraints, repairs violations, and only emits a protocol after successive correction. The "agents" are less important than the repeated cycle of proposal, diagnosis, and restoration of admissibility.</p>
<p data-start="2063" data-end="2490">One limitation is that the authors largely present this as an engineering result. They demonstrate empirically that reasoning, decomposition, tools, and self-correction help, but they do not develop a theory explaining <strong data-start="2282" data-end="2289">why</strong> these mechanisms should work together. The paper therefore provides strong experimental evidence for repair-based workflows but stops short of deriving a general mathematical principle governing them.</p>
<p data-start="2492" data-end="2775" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">I think this paper would make an excellent empirical citation for your repair program because it independently demonstrates that successful autonomous systems rely on maintaining and restoring admissibility throughout a computation rather than simply producing an output in one pass.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="z-0 flex min-h-[46px] justify-start"><div aria-label="Acciones de respuesta" class="touch:-me-2 touch:-ms-3.5 -ms-2.5 -me-1 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-y-4 p-1 select-none touch:w-[calc(100%+--spacing(3.5))] -mt-1 w-[calc(100%+--spacing(2.5))] duration-[1.5s] focus-within:transition-none hover:transition-none touch:pointer-events-auto pointer-events-none [mask-image:linear-gradient(to_right,black_33%,transparent_66%)] [mask-size:300%_100%] [mask-position:100%_0%] motion-safe:transition-[mask-position] group-hover/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-hover/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] group-focus-within/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-focus-within/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] has-data-[state=open]:pointer-events-auto has-data-[state=open]:[mask-position:0_0]" role="group" tabindex="-1" style="mask-position: 0% 0%;"><button type="button" class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-surface-hover rounded-lg" aria-label="Copiar respuesta" data-testid="copy-turn-action-button" data-state="closed"><span class="flex items-center justify-center touch:w-10 h-8 w-8"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="icon"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-c74d0474.svg#ce3544" fill="currentColor"></use></svg></span></button><button type="button" class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-surface-hover rounded-lg" aria-label="Buena respuesta" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="good-response-turn-action-button" data-state="closed"><span class="flex items-center justify-center touch:w-10 h-8 w-8"><svg xmlns="http:/